  Irish Maeve, Niall.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luasaigh</b>, an altered form of <b>Mac Cluasaigh</b>, a Cork name meaning ‘son of <i>Cluasach</i>’, a byname originally denoting someone with large or otherwise noticeable ears (from <i>cluas</i> ‘ear’).","English: variant of   Luce   1."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":42,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":67,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":80,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Lucy was born about 1248, in Up Holland, Lancashire, England as the daughter of Roger de Lucy. She married Thomas de Helbeck II. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1248–":"umbes 1248–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","1251–1297":"1251–1297","1278–1318":"1278–1318","1213–1274":"1213–1274","1297":"1297","Abt 1248":"umbes 1248","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1213":"1213","1278":"1278","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Warcop, Westmorland, England":"Warcop, Westmorland, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1248–":"noin 1248–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1248–Female":"1248–Kuollut","1251–1297":"1251–1297","1278–1318":"1278–1318","1213–1274":"1213–1274","1297":"1297","Abt 1248":"noin 1248","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1213":"1213","1278":"1278","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Warcop, Westmorland, England":"Warcop, Westmorland,